"'''SexyBack'''" is a song by American singer<U+2013>songwriter [[Justin Timberlake]] from his second studio album, ''[[FutureSex/LoveSounds]]'' (2006). It was released on July 7, 2006, by [[Jive Records]] as the lead single from the album. The song was co-written and produced by Timberlake, [[Timbaland]], and [[Danja|Nate "Danja" Hills]].

In discussion of the song, Timberlake revealed that he went "left", in regards to going more rock in the way he sang the song.<ref name="vineyard" /> He described the song as musicians [[David Bowie]] and [[David Byrne]] "covering" [[James Brown]]'s 1970 song "[[Get Up (I Feel Like Being a) Sex Machine|Sex Machine]]".<ref name="mX" /> The song features Timbaland on [[backing vocals]], while Timberlake's voice is [[process music|processed]] with distorted vocals. The musiscape in "SexyBack" features a pounding bass beat, electronic chords, and [[beat box]] sounds. The song received mixed reception by many contemporary critics.

The track entered the top ten on most singles charts, topping several of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine's component charts, including the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], [[Pop 100]], [[Hot Dance Airplay]], and [[Hot Digital Songs]] charts. "SexyBack" also became Timberlake's first number one single on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, staying seven weeks at the top spot. Internationally, the single peaked in the number one position in the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming Timberlake's first single to reach number one. In Australia, the track peaked at number one for two consecutive weeks at the top becoming Timberlake's second number one single.

"SexyBack" was certified 3x platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) and 6x platinum by [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA). The track won [[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]] at the [[49th Grammy Awards|2007 Grammy Awards]]. In addition, the song won Timberlake the [[People's Choice Award]] for Favorite R&B song and the Male Artist of the Year at the [[2007 MTV Video Music Awards]]. The music video was filmed in June 2006 and Timberlake's decision to work with director [[Michael Haussman]] was for the latter of his work in [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s 1994 music video "[[Take a Bow (Madonna song)|Take a Bow]]".<ref name="vineyard" />

==Background==
"SexyBack" was written and produced by Justin Timberlake, [[Timbaland]], and [[Danja|Nate "Danja" Hills]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Grammy Nominations; 2006 nominees|date=2006-12-08|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=E.32}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/chillis-gnarls-dixies-win-early-awards/2007/02/12/1171128859329.html|title=Chillis, Gnarls, Dixies win early awards|date=2007-02-12|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=2009-09-15}}</ref> In December 2005, Timberlake began working on his second album, ''[[FutureSex/LoveSounds]]'', the follow-up to his 2002 album ''[[Justified]]''. Within three weeks, "SexyBack" was one of several songs that were recorded.<ref name="rolling">{{cite news|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/11514699/cover_story_justin_timberlake_revs_up_his_sex_machine/5|title=Justin Timberlake Revs Up His Sex Machine|last=Scaggs|first=Austin|date=2006-09-06|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|page=5|accessdate=2009-05-16}}</ref> In September 2006, Timberlake told ''[[The Malay Mail|The Weekend Mail]]'' that "SexyBack" was the "second or third song" he did with Timbaland in a list of 10 songs they recorded for the album. "It was just an experiment gone right from the sort of synthesizer influence to the distorted vocals", said Timberlake. "It's one of the songs that the more you listen to it its just hook after hook after hook. Its just one of those 'flow off the top of your head' tracks, in terms of melody. We wanted to keep it lose and not too rehearsed, it's one of those very experimental records though."<ref>{{cite journal|title=Just Justin|date=2006-09-23|work=[[The Malay Mail|The Weekend Mail]]|page=28}}</ref> Timberlake revealed to [[MTV News]] that he went "left", regarding going more rock, not in how he developed the song, but in the way he sang the song. "I wanted to sing the song like a rock and roll singer, not an R&B singer. That's the approach."<ref name="vineyard">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1535791/20060706/timberlake_justin.jhtml|title='Back' In Style: Justin Timberlake Mixes Funk, Rock On New Single|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|date=2006-07-06|publisher=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref>

In another interview, Timberlake said that he modeled himself on musicians [[David Bowie]] and [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], and described the song as Bowie and [[David Byrne]] covering [[James Brown]]'s 1970 song "[[Get Up (I Feel Like Being a) Sex Machine|Sex Machine]]" and concluded with, "That's all of my influences for that song."<ref name="mX" /> Timberlake himself said that the song "doesn't qualify as rock or straight funk" and that he was happy with the description "club funk".<ref name="mX">{{cite journal|title=Goss & Glam|date=2006-07-10|work=[[mX (newspaper)|mX]]|page=026}}</ref> In another interview he said he was "keen for a new musical direction" following the release of his first album, ''Justified''. "I listened to the radio for a few months and thought, 'All this sounds like shit, what do I want to hear?'. That's really all I did. Everything's {{sic}} got so repetitive, everything sounds the same. I had to create something unique otherwise there's no point putting it out."<ref>{{cite journal|first=Kathy|last=McCabe|title=McCabe|date=2006-07-13|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)]]|page=045}}</ref>

==Music and lyrics==
{{listen|filename=SexyBackSample.ogg|title="SexyBack" excerpt
|description=The music of "SexyBack" is built around a pounding bass beat, electronic chords, and beat box sounds.|format=[[Ogg]]}}
"SexyBack" is an "urgent, pulsing track, a cocktail of soaring, distorted vocals and heavy, electronic chords threaded together with rap", according to Camilla Long from ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name="camilla" /> The song features an unabashed [[Time signature|4/4]] beat,<ref name"sal">{{cite news|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=957|title=Justin Timberlake|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=2006-09-05|work=[[Slant Magazine|Slant]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> a pounding bass beat and electronic sounds, and does not include Timberlake's "famous falsetto".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Daily Dish|date=2006-07-09|work=[[The Sun (Lowell)]]}}</ref> The song's musicscape includes two-note dirty electronic riffs,<ref name="nme">{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/justin-timberlake/8006|title=Justin Timberlake: SexyBack|date=2006-08-18|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> "leapfrogging keyboards",<ref name="melissa" /> beat box sound,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/12/AR2006091201573.html|title=Justin Timberlake, More Purr Than Growl|last=Stewart|first=Allison|date=2006-09-12|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> and incorporates the "same leaky faucet" sounds of musician [[Obie Trice]]'s 2004 song "[[The Set Up (song)|The Setup]]".<ref name="detriot">{{cite journal|first=Adam|last=Graham|title=Funk/R&B CD|date=2006-07-14|work=[[The Detroit News]]|page=08F}}</ref> In addition, the track features Timbaland on backing vocals.<ref name="lustig22">{{cite journal|first=Jay|last=Lustig|title=Timberlake surely in sync with his female fans|date=2006-09-04|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|page=22}}</ref>

Timberlake's voice in the song is [[process music|processed]],<ref name="melissa">{{cite journal|first=Melissa|last=Ruggieri|title=Justin Timberlake|date=2006-07-13|work=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|page=G-10}}</ref> slowed down to where his voice is unrecognizable,<ref name="detriot" /> with muffled vocals.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Hunter|last=Hauk|title=Pop stars bring their summer sexy|date=2006-06-28|work=[[Quick (newspaper)|Quick]]|page=16}}</ref> The song also features Timberlake's "low register distorted vocals."<ref name="lamb">{{cite news|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/sexyback.htm|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2014> SexyBack|last=Lamb|first=Bill|date=2006|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> Timberlake revealed that the vocals in the song were influenced by Prince.<ref name="camilla" /> In further discussion of the song, Timberlake said that the chorus was "very James Brown-ish, call out and repeat, like 'Sex Machine'." He wrote the track "from top to bottom. 'I'm bringing sexy back, yeah! I'm bringing. . .' It's a very physical song, meant to provoke&nbsp;... sexual dance. 'Sex Machine' is the closest reference."<ref name="camilla">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2006/jul/14/justintimberlake|title=Observermail preview: Justin Timberlake interview|last=Long|first=Camilla|date=2006-07-14|work=[[The Observer]]|publisher=''[[guardian.co.uk]]''|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> Timberlake said that the lyric, "bringing sexy back", was one of the first lines he came up with.<ref name="county">{{cite news|first=Jon|last=Breamu|title=Justin time&nbsp;<U+2014> Timberlake gets in sync with his sexy side on new beat-driven CD|date=2006-09-21|work=Ventura County Star}}</ref> In addition, he admitted that the song was not going to be titled "SexyBack", saying, "We weren't originally going to call it 'SexyBack'. I definitely didn't think it would become the most worn-out phrase of 2006. It just sounded like a nice opening to the song."<ref name="county" />

Adam Graham of ''[[The Detroit News]]'' noted that Timberlake sings about whips and chains,<ref name="detriot" /> while Bill Lamb of [[About.com]] said the song has a "bit of s&m tease about shackles and whips".<ref name="lamb" /> Furthermore, ''[[The Georgia Straight]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Martin Turenne said that Timberlake is "shackled to the bedpost, invites the crack of his mistress's whip."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straight.com/timberlake-strangely-ladylike?#|title=Timberlake strangely ladylike|last=Turenne|first=Martin|date=2006-09-14|work=[[The Georgia Straight]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> Ben Williams of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine wrote that Timberlake had been been working on his pickup lines, with "You see these shackles baby I<U+2019>m your slave<U+2009>/<U+2009>I<U+2019>ll let you whip me if I misbehave."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/reviews/20314/|title=The Men Who Would Be Prince|last=Williams|first=Ben|date=2006-09-11|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|accessdate=2009-09-03|page=1}}</ref> Jason Bracelin of the ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' reported that Timberlake sings about "threatening to steal your girl."<ref>{{cite journal|first=Jason|last=Bracelin|title=Bringing Sexy Back|date=2006-08-11|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|page=33J}}</ref> Charlie Brooker of ''[[The Guardian]]'', in regards to the lyric, "them other fuckers don't know how to act", wrote that Timberlake's translation is of him telling everyone in the world that they are a "clueless fornicator". Brooker continues that Timberlake "threatens us" by using "language so offensive" with the line, "You motherfuckers, watch how I attack".<ref name="brooker">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2006/sep/15/tvandradio.charliebrooker|title=Supposing ... Justin Timberlake's bringing sexy back|last=Brooker|first=Charlie|date=2006-09-15|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=''[[guardian.co.uk]]''|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> In addition, Brooker noted that the line, "If that's your girl you'd better watch your back", as Timberlake stating his intention to meddle in the private affairs of others.<ref name="brooker" /> Barry Schwartz of ''[[Stylus (magazine)|Stylus]]'' noted that the song features "pillow talk",<ref name="barry">{{cite news|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/justin-timberlake/futuresexlovesounds.htm|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2014> FutureSex/LoveSounds|last=Schwartz|first=Barry|date=2006-09-12|work=[[Stylus (magazine)|Stylus]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> in reference of the song's "sex-crazed lyrics".<ref name="lustig22"/>

==Critical reception==
[[File:Justin Timberlake <U+266B> SexyBack.jpg|thumb|right|215px|alt=In a stage, two men, both wearing white shirts, can be seen holding microphones. The first man, wearing a white long sleeve shirt, sings. While the other man, wearing a white shirt, dances to the music played. A crowd of people can also be seen holding up their cellphones.|Timbaland and Justin Timberlake performing "SexyBack" during Timberlake's 2007 [[FutureSex/LoveShow]] concert tour]]
In the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine review of the album, contributor Katy Kroll wrote that Timberlake "claims to be bringing 'sexy' back to pop music, and indeed he is. You can almost feel beads of sweat rolling off the title track and 'SexyBack' featuring Timbaland".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Katy|last=Kroll|title=FutureSex/LoveSounds|date=2006-09-16|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> Chris Willman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' was complimentary towards Timbaland, producer of the song, writing that Timbaland offers "tougher, trickier rhythms, minimal live playing, a plethora of hip-hop cameos, and a self-consciously hard, edgy club sensibility" to "SexyBack".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1532765,00.html|title=FutureSex/LoveSounds (2006)|last=Willman|first=Chris|date=2006-09-08|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> Russell Baillie of ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' noted, "The producer's angular synthesizer crunch is all over it &ndash; at best on the single 'SexyBack' where they dispense with a chorus, leaving the song sustained by its vocal fireworks, electrofunk and Timberland's repeated declaration that 'I'm bringing sexy back.{{' "}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=10402219|title=Justin Timberlake: FutureSex/LoveSounds|last=Baillie|first=Russell|date=2006-09-23|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> [[PopMatters]]' contributor Quentin B. Huff wrote that "SexyBack" was the "fraternal twin" to [[Nelly Furtado]]'s 2006 song "[[Promiscuous (song)|Promiscuous]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/justin-timberlake-futuresex-lovesounds/|title=A Tale of Two Tims|last=Huff|first=Quentin B. |date=2006-10-05|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> Andrew Murfett of ''[[The Age]]'' wrote that the song was a "raunchy club banger that slyly suppresses" Timberlake's customary falsetto. He continues, "it's introduced a new phrase into the pop cultural lexicon".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/cd-reviews/future-sexlove-sounds/2006/09/14/1157827079842.html|title=Future Sex/Love Sounds|last=Murfett|first=Andrew|date=2006-09-14|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsday]]'' was complimentary towards the song, writing that it was "Timberlake at his best, mainstreaming a combination of the wild, edgy dance-pop style of Basement Jaxx with Missy Elliott's more experimental hip-hop to create a boldly inventive sound that still pleases the masses."<ref>{{cite journal|first=Glenn|last=Gamboa|title=Melville, N.Y., Drops column|date=2006-09-12|work=[[Newsday]]}}</ref>

[[Kelefa Sanneh]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote: "...'SexyBack', a twitchy, emaciated track that shot to the top of the charts and also became an irritating catchphrase. (Suddenly everyone was bringing AdjectiveBack.)"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/11/arts/music/11choi.html?_r=3&oref=slogin&ref=music&pagewanted=all|title=New CD's|date=2006-09-11|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> Dagny Salas of ''[[North by Northwestern]]'' commented that Timberlake and Timbaland trade ridiculous lines, with "Get your sexy on/Go ahead, be gone with it" and "Dirty babe/You see these shackles/Baby I<U+2019>m your slave/I<U+2019>ll let you whip me if I misbehave."<ref name="north">{{cite news|url=http://www.northbynorthwestern.com/2006/10/340/album-review-of-justin-timberlakes-futuresexlovesounds/|title=Album Review of Justin Timberlake<U+2019>s ''FutureSex/LoveSounds''|last=Salas|first=Dagny|coauthors=Emily Vaughan|date=2006-10-09|work=[[North by Northwestern]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> Salas continued in her review that it was not a song that should be good, "but does that really matter when it<U+2019>s Good in the way that songs are during the summer [...] That kind of good makes songs like 'SexyBack' completely irresistible."<ref name="north" /> Matt Burns of ''[[The Post (Ohio newspaper)|The Post]]'' wrote, "Take the polarizing summer single 'SexyBack', a repetitive song with little structure that doesn't know when to stop, all centered on a ridiculous declaration. Somehow, it works."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-17625450_ITM|title=CD Review: Justin Timberlake brings 'SexyBack'.|last=Burns|first=Matt|date=2006-09-12|work=[[The Post (Ohio newspaper)|The Post]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> ''[[The Diamondback]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Michael Greenwald reported that "SexyBack" was "lyrically, musically and vocally the weakest song" on the album.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-17625743_ITM|title=CD Review: Justin Timberlake sounds best at center stage.|last=Greenwald|first=Michael|date=2006-09-12|work=[[The Diamondback]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> A writer of ''[[The State Journal-Register]]'' was not impressed with the song and concluded, with {{" '}}SexyBack' is the most annoyingly dumb song to hit ''Billboard''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s No. 1 since 'Hollaback Girl'".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Let's say bye, bye, bye to SexyBack|date=2006-09-14|work=[[The State Journal-Register]]|page=2A}}</ref> Guy Blackman of ''[[The Age|The Sunday Age]]'' wrote: "The distorted vocals and stilted production of first single 'Sexyback' make Timberlake's claim to be 'bringing sexy back'&nbsp;... seem almost laughable."<ref>{{cite journal|first=Guy|last=Blackman|coauthors=Martin Boulton; Tom Ryan; Ruth Brown; Nicole Bittar; Barney Zwartz|date=2006-09-17|work=[[The Age|The Sunday Age]]|page=48}}</ref>

Upon the song's release, it received divided opinions, which pleased Timberlake. "This is such a departure from the first record," said Timberlake. "More people might like it, less people might like it, but you can't call me a chicken."<ref>{{cite journal|first=Cameron|last=Adams|title=Timberlake's sexy solo|date=2006-07-13|work=[[Herald Sun]]|page=124}}</ref> Timberlake performed "SexyBack" and "[[My Love (Justin Timberlake song)|My Love]]" as a medley for the opening of the [[2006 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2006/#|title=2006 Video Music Awards|date=2006-08-31|publisher=MTV|accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref> The song won the [[People's Choice Award]] for Favorite R&B song at the [[33rd People's Choice Awards|2007 awards ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cbs3.com/national/33rd.Annual.People.2.278762.html|title=Depp Looms Large At People's Choice Awards|date=2007-01-10|publisher=[[CBS]]|accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref> At the [[49th Grammy Awards]], "SexyBack" won a [[Grammy Award]] in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Dance Recording|Best Dance Recording]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6347969.stm|title=Dixie Chicks earn Grammys triumph|date=2007-02-11|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref> At the [[2007 MTV Video Music Awards]], Timberlake won Male Artist of the Year for "SexyBack", "Let Me Talk To You / My Love", and "[[What Goes Around.../...Comes Around]]".<ref name="vma">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1566507/20070807/timberlake_justin.jhtml|title=MTV VMA Race Is On: Justin Timberlake, Beyonce Lead Nominations|last=Montgomery|first=James|date=2007-08-07|publisher=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=2009-05-18}}</ref>

==Chart performance==
"SexyBack" was commercially successful in the United States. The single debuted at number 90 in July 2006, on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. From number 31, it propelled to number one the following week.<ref name="timb">{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/10546|title=Justin Timberlake and Timbaland&nbsp;<U+2014> SexyBack|publisher=<U+03B1>Charts.us|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> "SexyBack" became Timberlake's first consecutive number one hit on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 from his ''Futuresex/Lovesounds'' album, becoming the first male artist since [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]] in 2004 to have three or more consecutive number one hits from one album.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Fred|last=Bronson|title=Chart Beat - 'Love' Conquers|date=2006-11-02|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> The single spent seven consecutive weeks in the number one position on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Marty|last=Franzen|title=Back on hot track Timberlake lands in area with' SexyBack Tour' stops|date=2007-03-23|work=[[Burlington County Times]]|page=3D}}</ref> In addition to the Hot 100, "SexyBack" also topped the following ''Billboard'' charts: [[Hot Dance Airplay]], [[Hot Dance Club Play]], [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]], [[Pop 100 Airplay]], [[Pop 100]], and [[Pop Songs|Top 40 Mainstream]] mainstream charts.<ref name="all">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:jbftxqwjld6e~T51|title=Justin Timberlake > Charts & Awards|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> "SexyBack" was certified 3x Platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite news|title=Justin Timberlake #1 at Radio in the U.S. and Europe With 'What Goes Around ... Comes Around'|date=2007-03-14|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=691381ED-73A8-ED48-8EB1-F323B95F3901|title=The Time Is Now|date=2007-07-17|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> This song made the then-seventh-biggest jump to number one in the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 history,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/search/?keyword=Justin+Timberlake#/news/timberlake-still-sexy-at-no-1-new-single-1003252478.story|title=Timberlake Still 'Sexy' At No. 1, New Single Keeps Climbing|date=2006-10-12|work=Billboard|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> climbing thirty spots from number 31 landing it at the summit of the chart on September 9, 2006.<ref name="timb" /> In a [[Nielsen SoundScan]] report, the song sold 250,000 as a digital download.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/index.jsp?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20070104005813|title=2006 U.S. Music Purchases Exceed 1 Billion Sales|date=2007-01-04|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>

In the United Kingdom, "SexyBack" debuted at number 13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] based solely on download sales one week prior to its physical release,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5291140.stm|title=Beyonce hits UK number one spot|date=2006-08-27|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> and ascended to the top of the chart the following week, becoming Timberlake's first UK number one single.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5310902.stm|title=Timberlake enjoys UK chart-topper|date=2006-09-03|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> On the Australian [[ARIA Charts]], "SexyBack" debuted at number one<ref name="ultra">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Justin+Timberlake&titel=SexyBack&cat=s|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2014> SexyBack|date=2006-09-09|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> and spent two consecutive weeks at the top becoming Timberlake's second number one single there (after "[[Rock Your Body]]" reached the summit in 2003),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Justin+Timberlake&titel=Rock+Your+Body&cat=s|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2014> Rock Your Body|date=2003-05-17|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> and has been certified 2x Platinum by ARIA Charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/ariacharts-accreditations-2006singles.htm|title=ARIA Charts&nbsp;<U+2014> Accreditations - 2006 Singles|date=2006|publisher=[[ARIA Charts]]|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> Also, in Canada and Austria, the single has peaked at number three and number five respectively,<ref name="lwin">{{cite journal|first=Nanda|last=Lwin|title=Bob Seger roars back with new album; Chart talk|date=2006-09-26|work=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|page=G10}}</ref> becoming his most successful single tied with his third released single "[[What Goes Around.../...Comes Around]]" in both nations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/song/11844|title=Justin Timberlake&nbsp;<U+2014> What Goes Around... Comes Around|publisher=<U+03B1>Charts|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> It has also been certified 6x Platinum in Canada.<ref name="CRIA">{{cite web|url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php|title=Canadian Recording Industry Association (CRIA): Certification Results|accessdate=2009-09-06|publisher=Canadian Recording Industry Association}}</ref>

In Sweden, "SexyBack" peaked at number four,<ref>{{cite journal|first=Paul|last=Sexton|title=Dylan's 'Modern Times' Rises To Euro Chart Zenith|date=2006-09-14|work=Billboard}}</ref> while in France it peaked at number eight<ref name="timb" /> becoming Timberlake's first top ten hit from the album, and would later score two more top ten singles with "[[My Love (Justin Timberlake song)|My Love]]" and "What Goes Around.../...Comes Around". The song has also peaked at number one in Germany, Ireland, New Zealand and Norway, and has peaked at number two in Switzerland and Belgium.<ref name="timb" />

==Music video==
The [[music video]] for "SexyBack" was directed by [[Michael Haussman]] and features Spanish actress [[Elena Anaya]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavanguardia.es/premium/publica/publica?COMPID=51277555513&ID_PAGINA=22088&ID_FORMATO=9&turbourl=false|title=La actriz Elena Anaya protagoniza el nuevo videoclip de Justin Timberlake|date=2006-07-24|work=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=2009-09-15}}</ref> The video was filmed in June 2006<ref>{{cite news|title=Timberlake and Diaz Recover From 'Rough Patch'|date=2006-06-28|publisher=[[World Entertainment News Network]]}}</ref> and shot in a luxury building in [[Barcelona]], [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Victoria|last=Newton|title=Lustin' bustin' Justin is back&nbsp;<U+2014> Bizarre|date=2006-07-26|work=[[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]]|page=21}}</ref> In discussion of the video filmed in Barcelona, Timberlake said: "Obviously we went for the architecture, the exteriors, the interiors <U+2014> the vibe in Spain is different than anywhere else in the world. It's so cool to shoot there, but the girls are also pretty hot, so that doesn't hurt either."<ref name="vineyard"/>

Timberlake decided to work with director Michael Haussman, following his work on [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s 1994 music video for "[[Take a Bow (Madonna song)|Take a Bow]]". "It's one of my favorite videos Madonna's ever done," Timberlake said. "Even today, I still remember the visuals, the images, how he captured her. A lot of times, Madonna seems like she's the person in control, and in that video, she seemed vulnerable. It was a cool thing to see."<ref name="vineyard"/> The video was first shown on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Making the Video]]'' on July 25, 2006.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Life: Short List|date=2006-07-25|work=[[The Press of Atlantic City]]|page=B1}}</ref>

The video starts off with a cable car looking over a large city (Barcelona, from the West looking East) and switches to a luxurious-looking hotel in Pla<U+00E7>a de Catalunya with Elena Anaya taking off her sweater. It then cuts to Timberlake in a different room; then to a club scene and Timberlake in front of a white background. The video alternates between those four viewpoints, with Timberlake and Anaya seeming to be spies in the hotel room and strangers in the club. At a certain point, Timberlake goes over to Anaya's room by jumping over to her balcony. Then when Anaya goes to check it out, Timberlake traps her and they have sex. In the club, it ends with Timberlake cornering Anaya in a bathroom stall. In the hotel room scene, Timberlake leaves by the same way he entered and moments later jumps back to the balcony before an explosion ensues. It ends with the figure of Anaya sitting in a chair beside a small television in which a kiss is frozen on the screen.

